Learn rhythm, the notes on your instrument and the natural scale at the very least. If on a guitar or piano some of the main chords. You need at least a foundation. Also you should be working at both. Being a good player and a good composer, they should be learned hand in hand. Merry Christmas

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114197232
Cleaner more efficient technique, accurate bends, smooth tasteful vibrato (not too fast!), good muting to eliminate unwanted overtones. What do? Tutorials specific to all these things, slow careful practice. Where the goal before was 'breddy gud enough' you're now aiming for close to flawless.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114197352
>what other techniques should i know?
It's not new techniques. Just less wasted motion, get chord changes snappy and effortless, think a lot about which fingers you're using to fret notes in such a way that moving around the neck is most efficient for the song in question. Same finger frets the same note in the same spot every time, with pick always going on an upstroke or a downstroke on that note (or finger plucks string in same way etc). Refinement is the idea. You know how you watch an experienced player flow through songs seemingly without any effort at all? That's the goal.

posts.com: I know punk started in the US with the Ramones, Richard Hell, etc., but in a way Robert Plant is correct. Punk was only ever an underground movement in the US until the 90s. In the 70s it was certainly a very underground phenomenon here. I think it can be hard for Americans to grasp how significant it was in the UK. The Sex Pistols had #1 hit singles. Punk completely changed the UK's popular music landscape. I think what Robert Plant is saying is, grunge had a comparable impact in American popular culture. It was a rejection of artifice and bullshit. Grunge WAS Seattle's punk/alternative underground, the same way the deep south's punk underground developed into sludge metal. Sure, only one faction of the grunge scene could really be called punk (Nirvana, Seaweed, Mudhoney), but other bands had those values. Pearl Jam sounded like arena rock, but Eddie Vedder was deeply into the indie, DIY mentality and for a while wanted to steer them in a stripped down, folky direction, influenced by Fugazi, which is why Vs. sounds the way it does. Soundgarden had complete contempt for mainstream metal and basically spat at it with Big Dumb Sex. The most anti-commercial bands in the whole scene were the borderline-sludge ones like Tad.

Quite possibly the most dogshit documentary I have ever watched

Ken Burns and Wynton Marsalis have the most traditional, absolute dogshit views on jazz in the history of humanity. I truly cannot believe I sat down through all of this over the course of a week. It’s absolutely abhorrent.

Basically, 9/10 episodes here focus on maybe the most boring periods of jazz. Yes, they were very important and necessary and I would’ve gladly sat through 5 episodes of it and have the last 5 cover 50s jazz onwards, but that’s not what happens. Instead all jazz past the 60s is shoved into a single episode.

A 19 hour jazz documentary where quite possibly the most creative period of musical history is shoved all into one episode. Not only that, it is treated like a joke.

It seems the creators of this documentary think that the swing shit is the pinnacle of jazz and the ultimate form of creation. The innovators of the late 50s through 70s are not only hardly mentioned but ripped to shreds.

It treats free jazz like it’s a joke. It treats spiritual jazz like it’s a joke. It treats any form of the avant garde like it’s a joke. It’s like if my racist great grandpa made a documentary on jazz. “Oh that old stuff with the funky beats was the good ol days, but when the music started getting political, that’s when I tune out.” type shit.

This shit is a fucking joke and to anyone who watched this with no knowledge of jazz I apologize for this shit having to be your source of knowledge for this absolutely amazing and beautiful genre. Ken Burns should never have touched jazz with a ten foot poll.

And just for good measure, I must stress one more time

Fuck Wynton Marsalis.

>>114183756
Ken Burns has always had an unfortunate habit of giving his consultants a huge amount of leeway in shaping the narrative of his documentaries. It's probably most egregious in The Civil War where his primary advisor and interviewee was some eccentric novelist (not even a historian lmao) who shilled for Lost Cause myths, which significantly narrowed and sanitized the scope of the series; and more recently it turned up in Country Music where his reliance on testimony from Nashville veterans led to an over-emphasis on country as a monolithic mainstream industry and insular community centered around totems like Music Row and the Oprey, while majorly important artists and scenes elsewhere in the country are either skimmed over or completely ignored.
With Jazz, having Marsalis, Crouch and Murray as his main consultants was a horrifically shortsighted choice. Bringing in three of the most infamously stubborn bop and swing purists in jazz criticism was always going to guarantee that avant-garde and fusion would be almost totally marginalized and the decades since the free jazz and fusion revolutions would get the same treatment as an in memorium reel at an awards show, giving the impression that jazz is dead or irrelevant and genteel in the same way classical is perceived.

In USA, it's not uncommon for people to be unfamiliar with classical music, or to have trouble distinguishing between different Scandinavian countries. However, that doesn't mean that the influence of classical music on electronic music subgenres in these countries should be overlooked.

In the case of dungeon synth, a subgenre of electronic music that originated in the 1980s and 1990s, it's interesting to consider the distinct musical influences that have shaped its development in different parts of Scandinavia.

For example, in Sweden, it's been suggested that the keyboard and organ music of ABBA, the iconic Swedish pop group, had a significant influence on the development of dungeon synth in the country. ABBA's music is known for its catchy and upbeat sound, and it's not surprising that it would have an impact on other musical genres.

On the other hand, in Norway, it's been suggested that the music of composer Grieg had a greater influence on the development of dungeon synth. Grieg was a 19th century Norwegian composer known for his romantic and nationalistic style, and his music often featured prominent piano and orchestral elements.

While these two examples may seem quite different at first glance, it's worth noting that the use of organs and keyboards is a common feature in both ABBA's music and dungeon synth, and it's possible that this shared element contributed to the influence of ABBA's music on Swedish dungeon synth.

Overall, it's fascinating to consider the various musical influences that have shaped the development of different subgenres of electronic music, and how these influences can vary from one country to another.

Dungeon synth is a style of Electronic music that focuses on evoking epic, atmospheric soundscapes associated with fantasy and medieval settings. Artists primarily utilize synthesizers, keyboards, and drum machines to create Ambient and orchestral textures, with vocals, samples, acoustic instruments, and lo-fi production also occasionally employed. Due to its instrumental nature, dungeon synth musicians concentrate on storytelling through music and create specific sceneries often inspired by mythology, literature of fantasy writers such as J.R.R. Tolkien, video games, and tabletop RPGs like Dungeons & Dragons. The term was coined on March 17th, 2011, in Andrew Werdna's first post on Dungeon Synth Blog, where he described it as "the sound of the ancient crypt."

Early influences of the genre include Berlin School acts such as Tangerine Dream and Klaus Schulze creating layered, synthesizer-led textures inspired by space and futurism. Jim Kirkwood took these hypnotic soundscapes and used them to produce fantasy-oriented atmospheres. Another wave of influence came from the Neoclassical Darkwave sound of Dead Can Dance, who developed their compositions using synths and drum machines. Dark Ambient and Martial Industrial were also important influences, as plenty of early examples of dungeon synth were guided by those styles.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=85I6tnjsb9I
The first dungeon synth artists emerged in the early-mid 1990s in the wake of the Norwegian Black Metal scene. Mortiis started his solo career after he departed from Emperor and embraced simply-produced, medieval-esque compositions. Varg Vikernes often utilized ambient/dungeon synth interludes on Burzum records, and after his imprisonment, he released his two "prison albums," Dauði Baldrs and Hliðskjálf, which were recorded using a synthesizer and a tape recorder. Other significant projects from the first era include Depressive Silence, who dabbled in ethereal, lush, and lo-fi soundscapes, and Summoning, who accentuated their Symphonic Black Metal sound with keyboards and drum machines.

In the 2000s, dungeon synth experienced a decline, where acts discontinued or went in different directions with their style. The genre began regaining interest in the early 2010s, with blogs and sites such as Andrew Werdna's Dungeon Synth Blog and the Dungeon Synth Archives Youtube channel introducing the genre to new listeners. Werdna's Blog in particular helped establish a more formal description of its sound. Projects which contributed to the revival wave, such as Erang, Lord Lovidicus, and Fief, were inspired by the 1990s acts, while Bandcamp became the successor to the tape trading community. Due to its rising popularity in the late 2010s and 2020s, dungeon synth artists began experimenting with creating different, more specific moods with Winter Synth (Yearner, Inoriand) exploring cold soundscapes while Comfy Synth (Grandma's Cottage, Earthencloak) delved into cozy, nostalgic atmospheres, dropping the epic aesthetic.

Vaporwave has continued to remain interesting for a variety of reasons. It's use of retro graphics, neon colors, and slowed-down or pitch-shifted samples of music from the 1980s and 1990s makes it distinct from other genres. This aesthetic has had a lasting impact on popular culture, influencing fashion, art, and even advertising.

Another reason vaporwave is still interesting is that it is a genre that is constantly evolving and being reinterpreted by new artists. Despite being a relatively niche genre, vaporwave has inspired numerous sub-genres and spin-offs, such as future funk, mallsoft, and hypnagogic pop, which have added new layers of complexity and innovation to the genre.

Vaporwave has also gained a cult following online, with a vibrant community of fans and artists who are dedicated to exploring and celebrating the genre. This community has helped to keep vaporwave alive and relevant, even as other trends have come and gone.

Overall, vaporwave's enduring appeal can be attributed to its unique aesthetic, its ability to evolve and adapt, and its dedicated community of fans. Even in 2022, vaporwave remains an interesting and influential genre that continues to inspire and captivate listeners around the world.

>>114197381
Advaitic Songs is simply masterful and elegant. The album title comes from a Hindu system of thought in which the 'Advaita' (literally 'non-dual') refers to the self (Atman) and the whole (Brahman). Everything is a part of and made of one nondual conciousness.
The cover Represents an orthodox icon of John the Baptist. This figure is of great importance to understand the main themes of the album.
According to biblical sources, he announced the arrival of the Messiah.
"And John Called To Him two of His disciples, and Sent Them to Jesus, Saying: Art thou he That art to come, or look we for another?"
Luke 7:19
John the Baptist is also present in the Qur'an as one of the great prophets who preceded Muhammad.
"[He was Told] 'O Zechariah, indeed We give you good tidings of a boy Whose name will be John. We have not assigned to any before [this] name.'"
Surat Maryam 19:7
"[Allah] said, 'O John, take the Scripture with determination.' And We Gave HIM Judgement [while yet] a boy."
Surat Maryam 19:12
Thus he is the constant presence of the precursor in the spiritual life of humanity.
So here we are transported to another place, another time; an archaic time among the sandy dunes and the incense fumes, in which all humanity began.
Amid Middle Eastern sounds, mantra and prayers, the album stands out for two main reasons: originality and evocativity.
The innovative aspect of the album is given mainly by the different sounds that compose it. where once was a privileged one great cyclical riff, now there is an enrichment of instrumental and compositional details in which the basic riff is allowed to flow between the various instruments.
While the evocative side stems from Middle Eastern-flavored percussions, strings played sometimes softly and others more intense decorated with piano chords, the whole fused into an ancestral and timeless spirituality.
Let's smoke some psychoactive weed and begin our mystical trip!

Addis (05:33)
The song begins with a female voice who recites the Mahamrityunjava Mantra (The 'Great Death-conquering Mantra', or, 'Mantra for Healing'):
"Om tryambakam yajāmahe sugandhim pushti-vardhanam
urvā rukamiva bandhanān mrityormukshīya māmritāt"
(Rigveda 7.59.12)
Here's a simple translation of these two verses:
"Om, Three-eyed one, I meditate on you, who increase fragrance and nourishment. From powerful disease, bondage and death free us into immortality."
For the mantra could be effective, it is repeated for almost the whole song, giving it a sense of mysticism, thanks also to the excellent water-drop effect of the tabla drums, timbrels and strings sound.
What a great start, isn't it?


State of Non-Return (06:07)
It is true, there are few moments of this album where you can identify that active duo of bass and drums typical of their earlier work, and this song is one of those moments. In fact it starts with a good cymbals work and a bass riff that winds in the middle. However, the selfishness (if one may define it so) of these gives out to leave space for a more subtle and moderate conclusion.


Gethsemane (10:26)
Excellent bass work that shifts to cello and then returns, like a sort of call and response between these two instruments. I also appreciate the drums that keeps its attention to the whole song even with the soft sound of timbrels. Awesome bass riffs before the end.

Sinai (10:20)
The song starts with the Talbiyah, which is a muslim prayer recited by the pilgrims who intend to perform the Hajj (the pilgrimage to Mecca).
"Labbaika Allahumma, Labbaik, Labbaika laa shareeka laka labbaik. Innal-Hamda wanni'mata laka wal mulk La shareeka lak."
Which means: "Here I am, O Allah, here I am, there is no partner for you, Here I am! Surely, all praise and blessings are for you and dominion is Yours. There is no partner for you."
As the prayer ends so begins the bass riff, repetitive, mantric, followed by the drums and then the cello. The whole played on a mystic melody which goes on until the end.


Haqq al-Yaqin (11:25)
Haqq al-Yaqin is the third and last level of Yaqin (generally translated as 'knowledge' or 'certainity'). This last level is known as the knowledge by the unity of subject and object, the total reality of Certainty, i.e. as supreme truth. This last stage is attainable by an elect few. Once destroyed Maya through the knowledge of Brahman you shall complete the path of walayah or sainthood.
The whole song sounds tribal and mystical. Tabla drums, cymbals work and the cello are fused into something metaphysical and brilliant. As soon as the cello stops the whispering voice of are Godman takes its place and vice versa.
So spiritual and masterful!

posts.com: Didn't know she waited until she was old to start putting out Christmas albums. At 50 her voice still sounds good enough here and the album fortunately sticks to a '50s style arrangement and doesn't try gimmicky late 70s production (imagine the horror of this being a disco album). She guested on a Debby Boone Christmas album in the '80s and then put out a couple more Christmas records with Concord in her final decade. The last one was from '96. Voice is still ok there but she's sounding a little short on breath.

https://archive.org/details/78_silver-bells_doris-day-evans-livingston-george-siravo_gbia0040585b/Silver+Bells+-+Doris+Day+-+Evans+-+Livingston.flac
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CuMv-rPF45o
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JLYqkscuZkA

She originally recorded Silver Bells in 1950 and then it opened her '64 Xmas album. The 45 release of the original had no bass which was a common trait of Columbia 45s in the '50s; the 78 one sounds better and has more depth. As for the 1964 rerecord, it's typical hi fi stereo LP slickness and her vocals are a bit more more ornate than the original.

listened to the whole thing twice. first off, i am very partial to chipmusic and chip influences, which i assume you're going for (i used to be an admin of 8bitcollective;)) the tune offers a nice, sort of cinematic feeling, sort of reminds me of a cheaper (sorry!) starscream/infinity shred. there are a few arps that sound... wrong, as in wrong notes; particularly the ones on the chords that are meant to provide "tension". i have no issues with tunes that drone on the same theme for a long time (see: my tune below), but i think this doesn't do quite enough to keep the listener engaged. the production is a bit loose as well; the low arps are a bit lost in the mix and muddy. i wish the snare was more punchy and turned up in the mix as well. the kick is a little "loose" too; maybe try adding some higher frequency components to it. i wish it built up to a bigger "wall of sound" feeling as it progresses. it feels like a post rock tune that never reaches its climax. anyway, sorry for blogspam, nice tune mate.

here's something i've been working on; spent every waking moment this past week working on it. back at home now for xmas and i have an old mandolin and banjo here that i'm gonna bring back to record on this (and other) tune(s). i've always wanted to write this kind of music but been too self conscious/thought it was too self-indulgent, but decided to say fuck it.

https://vocaroo.com/15RVcpvPpw6f
